    "narrative": "For LawDog on April 12, the outfield provides our highest upside, led by **Daulton Varsho** (69.94) and **Brendan Donovan** (68.26). **Varsho** benefits from a high-floor matchup against Bradley, T, carrying a strong score driven by a favorable park factor and a 10% platoon advantage. Simultaneously, **Donovan** exploits a soft matchup against the 4.57 xERA of Bolton, maximized by his leadoff spot and a significant 14% platoon boost. **Bryson Stott** (68.82) remains an essential start in the infield; while facing the formidable Gallen, **Stott** thrives on a 13% platoon edge and a park factor that pushes his overall efficiency into the elite range for the day.\n\nThe most challenging decision centered on **Jos\u00e9 Ram\u00edrez** (55.12). Despite his superstar status, the combination of facing a high-caliber arm in Sale and historical BvP struggles pushed his score toward the lower end of our starting threshold. He narrowly remains in the lineup over **Gleyber Torres** (53.93), whose marginal score against Alcantara, S failed to overcome the cumulative efficiency provided by our starters. **Yainer Diaz** (39.08) was the most notable exclusion, falling beneath our 40.0 floor due to a severe 19% downgrade against the elite SP skill of Gilbert, L. \n\nWe are monitoring the **Matt Chapman** (58.27) start closely. While he benefits from a 16% park boost against Povich, the threat of an elite hold pitcher\u2014who successfully neutralizes our prioritization of SB\u2014caps his upside. Similarly, **Taylor Ward** (67.47) and **Jeremiah Jackson** (62.33) are locked in against Houser; both benefit from an extreme 16% park advantage, though we must be mindful that **Jackson**\u2019s order spot (#9) is acting as a drag on an otherwise high-value matchup. With **Luis Arraez** unavailable, we are relying on the depth of the outfield to carry the load today.",
